B22 - Enhance the cybersecurity of a website from your community

Objective
The goal of this activity was to analyse a community-relevant website and identify potential cybersecurity improvements to enhance user safety and data protection.

Method
I selected the website realestate.com.au and evaluated its publicly visible security features based on common cybersecurity principles such as authentication, encryption, user data protection, and account security.

Findings
- The website uses HTTPS encryption, ensuring secure communication between users and platform.
- User accounts are used for saved searches, enquiries, and property alerts, meaning personal data is stored and processed.
- Login-based features indicate reliance on password-based authentication as the primary security method.
- Limited visible enforcement of advanced authentication mechanisms such as mandatory multi-factor authentication.

Recommended Improvements
- Implement mandatory MFA for all user accounts to improve login security.
- Strengthen password security policies, including detection of weak or previously breached passwords.
- Improve session management, such as automatic logout after inactivity to reduce hijacking risks.
- Enhance phishing awareness messaging, warning users about fake property listings or scam emails.
- Provide clearer account security dashboards showing login hostory and device activity.

Outcome
The analysis identified several areas where the website could improve its cybersecurity posture, particularly around authentication strength and user account protection.

Reflection
This activity demonstrated how large public platforms that handle personal data still rely heavily on password-based authentication. It reinforced the importance of layered secuity measures such as MFA, session control, and user awareness to reduce cyber risks.
